{#- §06 ECONOMICS (why fractional not full-time — prose + pull-quote) — sand -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="fractional-cfo-economics" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Why fractional, not full-time</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="max-width:24ch;margin-bottom:24px;">The economics of CFO work between $1M and $50M.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A full-time CFO at a U.S. business between $1M and $50M revenue typically costs $250,000 to $400,000 fully loaded &mdash; base, bonus, equity, benefits, employer taxes, recruiting, severance reserve. That&rsquo;s before an office, an analyst to support the CFO, or the accounting software the CFO will demand.</p>
      <p>Most businesses in this range don&rsquo;t need 40 hours a week of CFO work. They need 20 to 60 hours a month of senior strategic work, delivered consistently. The remaining 30+ hours of a full-time CFO&rsquo;s week gets absorbed by operational tasks better handled by a controller, a bookkeeper, or software &mdash; at a fraction of the cost.</p>
    </div>
    <blockquote class="opquote" style="margin-top:28px;"><blockquote>The fractional CFO model isn&rsquo;t a discount &mdash; it&rsquo;s a <strong>match</strong>. Senior judgment for the decisions that need senior judgment; operational accounting for the work that doesn&rsquo;t. Fractional delivers senior strategic work at <strong>15&ndash;30% of full-time cost</strong> &mdash; and when TechBrot runs the bookkeeping underneath, the CFO works from clean books instead of building them.</blockquote></blockquote>
  </div>
</section>

